{{ pc.endStandardSection() }}

{{ pc.standardSection('id="native-apis"') }}
  <h3 id="native-web-apis">Native Web Platform APIs</h3>
  <p>Recent web platform additions that address related (but distinct) problems:</p>

  <h4>Popover API &amp; Top Layer</h4>
  <p>
    The Popover API (baseline 2024) provides native support for tooltips, menus, and non-modal overlays with automatic top-layer rendering.
  </p>
  {% highlight "html" %}
<button popovertarget="my-popover">Toggle Popover</button>
<div id="my-popover" popover>
  Popover content - automatically in top layer
</div>
  {% endhighlight %}
  <ul style="font-size: 0.9rem; color: var(--color-text-muted);">
    <li><strong>Top Layer:</strong> Renders above all z-indexes without manual z-index management</li>
    <li><strong>Light Dismiss:</strong> Built-in click-outside and ESC key handling</li>
    <li><strong>Limitation:</strong> No context preservation; the popover is still a regular DOM descendant</li>
  </ul>

  <h4>CSS Anchor Positioning</h4>
  <p>
    Anchor positioning (Chrome 125+, Interop 2025) allows elements to position relative to "anchor" elements, even across stacking contexts.
  </p>
  {% highlight "css" %}
.tooltip {
  position: fixed;
  position-anchor: --trigger;
  top: anchor(bottom);
  left: anchor(center);
}
  {% endhighlight %}
  <ul style="font-size: 0.9rem; color: var(--color-text-muted);">
    <li><strong>Top Layer Compatible:</strong> Works with popover and dialog elements</li>
    <li><strong>Scroll Tethering:</strong> Anchored elements scroll with their anchors</li>
    <li><strong>Limitation:</strong> Solves positioning, not context or event propagation</li>
  </ul>
{{ pc.endStandardSection() }}

{{ pc.standardSection('id="wicg-portals"') }}
  <h3 id="wicg-portals-note">Note: WICG Portals (Different Concept)</h3>
  <div class="content-box" style="background: rgba(251, 191, 36, 0.1); border: 1px solid rgba(251, 191, 36, 0.3);">
    <p style="margin: 0; font-size: 0.9rem;">
      <strong>Important:</strong> The <a href="https://wicg.github.io/portals/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">WICG Portals proposal</a> addresses a completely different problem: seamless navigation transitions between pages. It introduces a <code>&lt;portal&gt;</code> element for embedding and activating other pages (similar to an iframe that can be "promoted" to the top-level document). This is unrelated to the React-style portals that Web Portals aims to standardize.
    </p>
  </div>
{{ pc.endStandardSection() }}

{{ pc.standardSection('id="gap-analysis"') }}
  <h3 id="gap-analysis">Gap Analysis</h3>
  <p>What frameworks provide that native HTML lacks:</p>
  <div style="overflow-x: auto; max-width: 100%;">
    <we-data-table><table style="min-width: 600px;">
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Capability</th>
          <th>Framework Portals</th>
          <th>Native HTML</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td>Render to arbitrary DOM location</td>
          <td>Yes</td>
          <td>Manual (appendChild)</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Preserve context from logical ancestors</td>
          <td>Yes (virtual tree)</td>
          <td>No - contexts follow DOM</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Event bubbling through logical tree</td>
          <td>Yes</td>
          <td>No - events follow DOM</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Escape stacking contexts</td>
          <td>Yes</td>
          <td>Yes (top layer, position: fixed)</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Automatic lifecycle management</td>
          <td>Yes</td>
          <td>No - manual cleanup required</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Declarative API</td>
          <td>Yes</td>
          <td>No</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table></we-data-table>
  </div>
  <p style="margin-top: 1rem;">
    <strong>Conclusion:</strong> The core gap is the concept of a "logical tree" that's independent of the DOM tree. Web Portals proposes using the injector hierarchy (from Web Injectors) as this logical backbone, enabling context queries, event proxying, and lifecycle management to follow the logical structure rather than the physical DOM.
  </p>
{{ pc.endStandardSection() }}

  </div>
</details>

{{ pc.standardSection('id="ssr"') }}
    <h3 id="ssr-contract">SSR Contract</h3>
    <p>
        This section defines the server-side rendering contract for <strong>Web Portals</strong>.
        Portals relocate content from a <em>logical</em> position (where the component authors it) to a <em>physical</em> position
        (where it renders in the DOM). The server MUST emit portal content at its logical position; the client relocates it during hydration.
    </p>

    <h4 id="ssr-server-output">Server Output Requirements</h4>
    <div class="comparison-table-wrapper mt-4">
        <we-data-table><table class="comparison-table">
            <thead>
                <tr>
                    <th>Feature</th>
                    <th>Server Output HTML</th>
                    <th>Notes</th>
                </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
                <tr>
                    <td><strong>Portal content (logical position)</strong></td>
                    <td>
<we-code-view><pre style="margin: 0; font-size: 0.8em;"><code>&lt;div class="card"&gt;
  &lt;!-- portal:modal-root --&gt;
  &lt;div class="modal" data-portal="modal-root"&gt;
    &lt;h2&gt;Confirm Delete&lt;/h2&gt;
    &lt;p&gt;Are you sure?&lt;/p&gt;
  &lt;/div&gt;
  &lt;!-- /portal:modal-root --&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;</code></pre></we-code-view>
                    </td>
                    <td>Server MUST render portal content at its <strong>logical position</strong> in the component tree, wrapped in comment boundary markers. The <code>data-portal</code> attribute identifies the target container.</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td><strong>Portal target container</strong></td>
                    <td>
<we-code-view><pre style="margin: 0; font-size: 0.8em;"><code>&lt;div id="modal-root"
  data-portal-target&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;</code></pre></we-code-view>
                    </td>
                    <td>Server MUST emit the portal target container as an empty element. The client moves content into it during hydration.</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td><strong>Multiple portals to same target</strong></td>
                    <td>Each portal at its own logical position with unique comment markers</td>
                    <td>Multiple components MAY portal to the same target. Order is determined by DOM source order of the logical positions.</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td><strong>Injector context</strong></td>
                    <td>Resolved from logical position</td>
                    <td>Server MUST resolve injector values from the portal's <strong>logical</strong> ancestors, not the target container's ancestors. See <a href="/projects/webinjectors/#ssr">Web Injectors SSR</a>.</td>
                </tr>
            </tbody>
        </table></we-data-table>
    </div>

    <h4 id="ssr-hydration-expectations">Client Hydration Expectations</h4>
    <ul class="list-disc ml-6 text-gray-600 text-sm">
        <li><strong>Content relocation:</strong> Client finds <code>&lt;!-- portal:... --&gt;</code> boundary markers, extracts the content, and moves it into the matching <code>data-portal-target</code> container.</li>
        <li><strong>Context preservation:</strong> The portal maintains a reference to its logical parent for injector resolution, event proxying, and lifecycle management — even after physical relocation.</li>
        <li><strong>Marker cleanup:</strong> Client MAY remove the comment boundary markers after relocation, or leave them for potential re-rendering.</li>
        <li><strong>Event proxying:</strong> Events dispatched on portaled content bubble through the <em>logical</em> tree (via the injector hierarchy), not the physical DOM tree.</li>
    </ul>

    <h4 id="ssr-progressive-baseline">Progressive Enhancement Baseline</h4>
    <p class="text-gray-600 text-sm">
        With zero JavaScript: portal content is visible at its logical position in the document flow.
        This means a modal's content appears inline where the component authored it, not in a separate overlay.
        The content is fully readable and accessible — it simply isn't relocated to its intended visual position.
        The empty target container is invisible (no content to display).
    </p>

    <h4 id="ssr-client-only">Client-Only Features</h4>
    <ul class="list-disc ml-6 text-gray-600 text-sm">
        <li><strong>Content relocation:</strong> Moving portal content from logical to physical DOM position</li>
        <li><strong>Event proxying:</strong> Bubbling events through the logical tree</li>
        <li><strong>Context bridging:</strong> Maintaining injector access across DOM boundaries</li>
        <li><strong>Lifecycle management:</strong> Automatic cleanup when the portal source unmounts</li>
        <li><strong>Dynamic portal creation:</strong> Programmatic portal instantiation at runtime</li>
    </ul>

    <div class="comparison-block" style="background: rgba(251, 191, 36, 0.1); padding: 1.25rem; border-radius: 8px; border-left: 4px solid #f59e0b; margin: 1.5rem 0;">
        <h4 id="ssr-implementor-note" style="margin-top: 0; color: #d97706; font-size: 1rem;">Implementor Note</h4>
        <p style="margin-bottom: 0; font-size: 0.95rem;">
            This contract defines compliance requirements. The build system or server framework
            is responsible for rendering portal content at the logical position with boundary markers
            and emitting empty target containers.
            Web Portals does not ship an SSR runtime — it ships this specification.
        </p>
    </div>
{{ pc.endStandardSection() }}

{{ pc.standardSection('id="protocol-embedded-deck"') }}
    <h3>Protocol — Embedded-Deck postMessage Contract</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-600 text-sm">
        Embeds a <strong>live, interactive deck</strong> inside another document via an iframe, with state
        isolation and a typed <code>postMessage</code> envelope as the only thing that crosses the frame
        boundary. The host page can drive the deck (go-to-slide, next/prev) and the embedded deck reports
        its state back (current address, active fragment, ended), so an embedded deck is deep-linkable
        independently of its host URL.
    </p>
    <div class="comparison-table-wrapper mt-4">
        <we-data-table><table class="comparison-table">
            <tr><th>Direction</th><th>Message</th><th>Carries</th></tr>
            <tr><td>host → deck</td><td><code>goto</code></td><td>a slide address (slide + optional fragment/vertical) to navigate to.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>host → deck</td><td><code>advance</code> / <code>retreat</code></td><td>step the sequence forward / back (fragment-aware).</td></tr>
            <tr><td>deck → host</td><td><code>state</code></td><td>current address, active fragment, total slides — emitted on every change.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>deck → host</td><td><code>ended</code></td><td>the sequence reached its final position (for host-driven autoplay chaining).</td></tr>
        </table></we-data-table>
    </div>
    <p class="text-gray-600 text-sm mt-3">
        Composes the <a href="../webintents/">Navigation</a> intent and the slide-addressing semantic — it
        <em>bridges</em> the navigation model across the iframe rather than duplicating it. State stays
        isolated in the embedded document; the host never reaches into the deck's DOM. Web Portals ships
        this specification; <a href="../frontierui/">Frontier UI</a> renders the embeddable deck. Homed
        here per the ratified distributed placement (<a href="/backlog/1175/">#1175</a>).
    </p>
{{ pc.endStandardSection() }}
